---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About PlainInfluence"
  description="PlainInfluence tracks political money — campaign donations, lobbying, and federal contracts from official federal sources."
>
  <section class="py-8 md:py-12">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">About PlainInfluence</h1>
      <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--color-muted)] [&_h2]:text-[var(--color-foreground)] [&_strong]:text-[var(--color-foreground)]">
        <p>
          PlainInfluence makes U.S. political finance data accessible to everyone. We combine three
          federal data sources — campaign contributions (FEC), lobbying disclosures (Senate LDA), and
          federal contracts (USAspending.gov) — into a single, searchable platform.
        </p>

        <h2>Our Data</h2>
        <p>All data comes directly from official federal sources:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Federal Election Commission (FEC)</strong> — Bulk candidate and committee data for the
          2024 election cycle. Tracks PAC contributions to political candidates.</li>
          <li><strong>Senate Lobbying Disclosure Act (LDA)</strong> — Lobbying registration and activity reports
          filed by registered lobbyists, 2023-2024.</li>
          <li><strong>USAspending.gov</strong> — Federal contract awards from the Federal Procurement Data System (FPDS).
          Shows which organizations receive government contracts and from which agencies.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Entity Resolution</h2>
        <p>
          The key innovation is <strong>entity resolution</strong> — linking the same organization across
          all three databases. A company like Boeing appears in FEC data as a PAC contributor, in Senate
          LDA data as a lobbying spender, and in USAspending as a federal contractor. We link these records
          to show the full picture of an organization's political influence.
        </p>

        <h2>What We Track</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>7,124 politicians</strong> who received PAC contributions</li>
          <li><strong>9,940 organizations</strong> linked across all three databases</li>
          <li><strong>79 lobbying issue areas</strong> from health care to defense</li>
          <li><strong>56 states and territories</strong> with aggregated data</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Not Affiliated</h2>
        <p>
          PlainInfluence is not affiliated with the FEC, the U.S. Senate, USAspending.gov, or any
          government agency. We are an independent data portal presenting public information.
        </p>

        <h2>About Kiznis.Studio</h2>
        <p>
          This portal is built and maintained by <strong>Kiznis.Studio</strong>, an independent data
          publishing studio. We build free, ad-supported portals that make U.S. government data
          accessible to everyone — no paywalls, no accounts, no data harvesting.
        </p>

        <h2>Important Disclaimer</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>This site is for informational purposes only.</strong> Political finance data is
          complex and subject to reporting lags. Entity resolution may occasionally link unrelated
          organizations with similar names. Always verify important information with official sources.
          This site does not endorse or oppose any political candidate or party.
        </p>

        <h2>Contact</h2>
        <p>
          For questions or feedback, email <a href="mailto:hello@plaininfluence.com">hello@plaininfluence.com</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
